        <h1>What the Lullaby Trust Actually Says About Baby Sleeping Bags — A Factory's Reading Notes</h1>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>Published: April 21, 2026</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>By Lianchuang Textile</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="container article-body">
      <div class="article-content">

        <p class="lead">
          Most factories that make baby sleeping bags will tell you they follow safety standards. Fewer will tell you why those standards exist, or what it actually costs to meet them in production. This article is our attempt at the latter.
        </p>

        <p>We've been making GOTS-certified baby sleeping bags for over sixteen years — from a time when the category was still unfamiliar to most buyers, and TOG ratings needed explaining at every trade meeting. Over that time, we've read a lot of guidelines. The ones from the <a href="https://www.lullabytrust.org.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lullaby Trust</a> are, in our view, the most useful — not because they're the strictest, but because they explain the reasoning behind each recommendation clearly enough that a manufacturer can actually act on them.</p>

        <p>What follows is our reading of their guidance, with the factory context that usually gets left out.</p>

        <h2>Why the Lullaby Trust</h2>
        <p>The Lullaby Trust is a UK-based charity focused on sudden infant death syndrome (SIDS) research and prevention. Since 1991, the safer sleep advice informed by their work has been associated with a reduction of over 31,000 infant deaths. They don't endorse individual products. They don't sell anything. Their guidance is purely evidence-based, updated as research evolves, and written for parents — which makes it unusually honest reading for a manufacturer.</p>
        <p>Their core position on sleeping bags is straightforward: a well-fitting sleeping bag is a safer alternative to loose blankets, because it cannot shift to cover a baby's face during sleep. That is the functional reason this product exists. Everything else follows from it.</p>

        <h2>What "Well-Fitting" Actually Requires</h2>
        <p>The Lullaby Trust is specific about fit: the sleeping bag must be fitted around the neck and shoulders so a baby cannot wriggle down inside. This sounds simple. In production, it is one of the harder things to get consistently right.</p>
        <p>The challenge is that most sleeping bags are sized by weight, not age — and the weight range within a single size can span several kilograms. A bag that fits snugly on a 6kg baby may have too much neck opening on a 4.5kg baby of the same stated size. Pattern development for this product requires iterative testing across the weight distribution of each size, not just the midpoint. Factories that have made this product for a long time accumulate that pattern data. Factories starting from scratch are guessing, then correcting.</p>

        <h2>TOG Ratings and What They Demand of a Factory</h2>
        <p>The Lullaby Trust recommends matching TOG to room temperature, with 16–20°C cited as the target range for a baby's sleep environment. A 1.0 TOG bag is appropriate for warmer rooms; 2.5 TOG for cooler ones. Weighted sleeping bags — a recent market trend — are explicitly not recommended for babies under one year, due to risks of overheating and breathing restriction.</p>
        <p>For a factory, TOG accuracy is a quality control problem, not a design problem. The TOG value is determined primarily by the weight and distribution of the filling. In bulk production, filling weight must be consistent across thousands of units. A unit filled at 10% below specification isn't just off-label — in a product whose safety case depends on thermal performance, it is a different product. This requires calibrated equipment, trained operators, and ongoing monitoring. It is not achieved by writing the right number on the care label.</p>

        <div class="tog-table">
