          </div>
          <div class="tog-row">
            <span class="tog-val">2.5</span><span>16–20°C</span><span>Recommended core range; cooler environments</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2>The Role of Fabric</h2>
        <p>The Lullaby Trust's guidance on temperature management points implicitly toward fabric choice: natural fibres regulate heat more responsively than synthetics, reducing the risk of a baby becoming too warm without a parent noticing. This aligns with what we observe in production.</p>
        <p>Organic cotton and bamboo behave differently from polyester in ways that matter for this application. They breathe. They respond to body temperature. They don't trap heat in the same way. GOTS certification — which governs our materials and production process — is not primarily a marketing credential. It is a manufacturing constraint that keeps synthetic shortcuts out of the supply chain.</p>
        <p>The Lullaby Trust does not prescribe specific fabrics. But the logic of their temperature guidance points consistently toward materials that thermoregulate, and away from those that don't.</p>

        <h2>Safety Standards Are a Floor, Not a Ceiling</h2>
        <p>One note worth highlighting from the Lullaby Trust's product guidance: a safety standard does not mean that a product reduces the risk of SIDS — it means the product meets a minimum threshold of general safety. EN 16781 (the European standard for baby sleeping bags) covers things like flammability and structural integrity. Passing it means the product won't fall apart or catch fire easily. It does not mean the TOG rating is accurate, the fit is correct, or the fabric choice is appropriate.</p>
        <p>We mention this not to diminish the value of certification, but because buyers sometimes treat a standard number as a complete answer. It isn't. The standard sets the floor. What a factory does above that floor is a separate question.</p>

        <h2>A Note on Experience</h2>
        <p>We started making this product when the category was new in Western markets — when the brands we were working with were still building their own understanding of what parents needed, and the production knowledge had to be developed alongside the product itself. That experience is not transferable in a specification sheet. It lives in pattern archives, in quality records, in the accumulated decisions about what to do when a fabric behaves unexpectedly or a new size range doesn't fit the way the measurements suggested it would.</p>
        <p>The Lullaby Trust's guidance has not changed dramatically over the years — the fundamentals of safe infant sleep are relatively stable. What has changed is our understanding of how to meet those fundamentals reliably, at scale, across different materials and markets.</p>

